-- PRESS DIGEST-Hong Kong - May 2
-- By Donny Kwok
-- Thu May 01, 2014 10:01PM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, May 2 (Reuters) - These are some of the leading stories in Hong Kong newspapers on Friday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST  -- Mainland visitors called for more signs pointing to public toilets in Hong Kong and help instead of confrontation from locals - as the row over a mainland toddler's urination on a Mong Kok street stretched into the "golden week" holiday. (http://link.reuters.com/keh98v) -- An increasing number of mainland developers are tapping private real estate funds to finance costly land acquisitions, an alternative to trust loans which have come under tight regulatory scrutiny. (http://link.reuters.com/qeh98v) -- State Grid Corp of China [STGRD.UL], China's largest electricity grid operator, has been told to prepare 1,000 workspaces for state inspectors to conduct an accountability audit of the company's chairman, Liu Zhenya, a source said. (http://link.reuters.com/seh98v)  THE STANDARD -- Hong Kong police are gearing up to mobilise around 10,000 officers to handle potential threats and chaos from the Occupy Central movement, which they fear could occur during the July 1 march. The date marks the 17th anniversary of the handover of Hong Kong from British to Chinese rule. (http://link.reuters.com/teh98v) -- Hong Kong is the 76th most miserable place out of 90 assessed in a study by a U.S. think tank Cato Institute. The mainland was 82nd and Taiwan 88th. (http://link.reuters.com/veh98v) -- China Rongsheng Heavy Industries Group <1101.HK> issued a third tranche of HK$1 billion ($129 million) convertible bonds this year after a huge net loss and cash outflow last year. (http://link.reuters.com/weh98v)  HONG KONG ECONOMIC TIMES  -- Cosmopolitan International Holdings Ltd <0120.HK> said it proposed to consolidate 10 existing shares into one consolidated share, and planned to issue about 4.4 billion open offer shares in the proportion of two shares for every consolidated share held, raising HK$436 million ($56 million).  MING PAO DAILY NEWS  -- China's online video program distributor LeTV is set to offer its services in Hong Kong in the third quarter, competing with the city's pay TV operators Cable TV and now TV.